# 9. Azure DevOps Pipeline

The CI/CD process is implemented using Azure DevOps YAML Pipelines.

The pipeline consists of two stages:

1. Continuous Integration (CI)
2. Continuous Deployment (CD)

The pipeline is automatically triggered whenever code is pushed to the **main** branch.

```yaml
trigger:
- main
```

This enables automatic build and deployment without manual intervention.

---

# 10. Pipeline Variables

The pipeline uses an Azure DevOps Variable Group.

```yaml
variables:
- group: Production-Variables
```

## Why Variable Groups?

Instead of hardcoding configuration values inside the YAML file, Azure DevOps allows common variables to be stored securely.

Examples include:

- .NET SDK Version
- Build Configuration
- Server Names
- Environment-specific settings

Benefits:

- Centralized configuration
- Easy maintenance
- Reusable across multiple pipelines
- Better security
- No need to modify YAML when values change

---

# 11. Agent Pool

The pipeline runs using a Self-Hosted Agent.

```yaml
pool:
  name: Default
```

## Why Self-Hosted Agent?

Initially, Microsoft Hosted Agents were considered, but the project required deployment to a private AWS EC2 instance using SSH.

A Self-Hosted Agent provides:

- Complete control over the execution environment
- Faster builds after initial setup
- Ability to access private infrastructure
- Custom software installation
- No dependency on Microsoft-hosted images

The agent executes every pipeline task sequentially.

---

# 12. Continuous Integration Stage

The Continuous Integration stage is responsible for validating the application and generating a deployment package.

Pipeline Flow:

```

Checkout
↓
Install .NET SDK
↓
Install Node.js
↓
Restore Packages
↓
Build Solution
↓
Run Unit Tests
↓
Publish Application
↓
Publish Build Artifact

```

---

# 13. Checkout Source Code

```yaml
- checkout: self
```

## Purpose

Downloads the latest source code from the GitHub repository to the build agent.

Without this step, the agent would have no application source code to build.

Azure DevOps automatically performs:

- Repository cloning
- Branch checkout
- Workspace creation

---

# 14. Install .NET SDK

```yaml
- task: UseDotNet@2
```

## Purpose

Installs the required .NET SDK version on the build agent.

The SDK is required for:

- Restore
- Build
- Test
- Publish

Without the SDK, none of the .NET CLI commands would execute successfully.

The version is supplied from the Variable Group.

Example:

```

DOTNET_VERSION=10.0.x

```

Benefits:

- Consistent builds
- Version control
- Easy upgrades

---

# 15. Install Node.js

```yaml
- task: UseNode@1
```

## Why Node.js?

Although the backend is developed using .NET, the application contains an Angular frontend.

Angular requires:

- Node.js
- npm
- Angular CLI

During the publish process, Angular is automatically compiled.

Without Node.js, the publish step would fail because npm commands could not execute.

The pipeline installs Node.js version 20.

```yaml
version: '20.x'
```

---

# 16. Restore Packages

```yaml
command: restore
```

## Purpose

Downloads all NuGet packages required by the solution.

Examples include:

- ASP.NET Core packages
- Entity Framework Core
- MediatR
- FluentValidation
- AutoMapper

These packages are stored in the local NuGet cache on the build agent.

Restore is executed before Build because the compiler requires all referenced libraries.

---

# 17. Build Solution

```yaml
command: build
```

## Purpose

Compiles the complete solution.

The build process performs:

- Syntax validation
- Dependency validation
- Reference resolution
- Compilation
- DLL generation

No deployment occurs during this stage.

The output is intermediate compiled binaries.

---

# 18. Run Unit Tests

```yaml
command: test
```

## Purpose

Executes automated unit tests before deployment.

Current pipeline executes:

```

Application.UnitTests

```

The objective is to validate business logic before creating the deployment package.

If any test fails:

- Build fails
- Artifact is not created
- Deployment does not start

This prevents defective code from reaching production.

---

# 19. Publish Application

```yaml
command: publish
```

## Purpose

Creates the deployment-ready application.

Unlike Build, Publish prepares everything required to run the application on another server.

The publish process performs:

- Build verification
- Dependency packaging
- Angular build
- Static file generation
- Runtime file generation
- Publish folder creation

---

## Angular Build Process

One interesting aspect of this project is that the Angular application is **not built using separate pipeline tasks**.

Instead, Angular is built automatically during the .NET publish process.

The Web project contains MSBuild targets that execute Angular commands.

Internally the publish process performs:

```

dotnet publish
↓
npm install
↓
Generate Angular API Client
↓
ng build
↓
Copy Angular files into wwwroot
↓
Create publish output

```

This is why installing Node.js is mandatory even though there are no explicit Angular build tasks in the YAML pipeline.

---

# 20. Publish Build Artifact

```yaml
PublishBuildArtifacts@1
```

## Purpose

Stores the published application as an Azure DevOps Artifact.

Artifact Name:

```

drop

```

The artifact contains:

- Published DLLs
- Configuration files
- Angular frontend
- Static files
- Runtime dependencies
- Web.zip

---

## Why Artifacts?

Artifacts separate the Build process from Deployment.

Instead of rebuilding the application during deployment, the exact same artifact produced by the CI stage is deployed.

Advantages include:

- Consistency
- Faster deployments
- Traceability
- Rollback capability
- Reusability

This approach follows standard DevOps best practices.

---

# CI Stage Summary

At the completion of the Continuous Integration stage, Azure DevOps has successfully:

- Downloaded the source code
- Installed all required tools
- Restored project dependencies
- Built the application
- Executed unit tests
- Published the application
- Generated a deployment artifact

No changes are made to the production server during this stage.

The output of the CI stage is a validated deployment package that is ready for release in the Continuous Deployment stage.



# 21. Continuous Deployment Stage

The Continuous Deployment (CD) stage is responsible for deploying the application built during the Continuous Integration stage to an AWS EC2 instance.

Unlike the CI stage, which validates and packages the application, the CD stage focuses on releasing the application to the target environment.

The deployment process is fully automated and is executed only after the CI stage completes successfully.

Pipeline Flow:

```

Download Artifact

↓

Verify Artifact

↓

Copy Artifact to AWS EC2

↓

Connect to EC2 using SSH

↓

Stop Running Application

↓

Create Backup

↓

Clean Previous Deployment

↓

Extract Latest Build

↓

Set File Ownership

↓

Start Application

↓

Verify Service

↓

Health Check

↓

Deployment Successful

```

---

# 22. Deployment Job

The deployment stage uses an Azure DevOps Deployment Job.

```yaml
deployment: DeployToEC2
```

Deployment jobs provide additional deployment tracking and are associated with Azure DevOps Environments.

Benefits include:

- Deployment history
- Environment tracking
- Approval support
- Audit logs
- Deployment visualization

---

# 23. Azure DevOps Environment

The deployment targets the following environment:

```yaml
environment: Production
```

Environments provide logical separation between deployment targets.

Typical enterprise environments include:

- Development
- Testing
- UAT
- Production

For this project, the application is deployed directly to the Production environment.

---

# 24. Download Build Artifact

```yaml
- download: current
  artifact: drop
```

## Purpose

The CI stage generated an artifact named **drop**.

The CD stage downloads this artifact before deployment.

The downloaded artifact contains:

- Published application
- DLL files
- Angular frontend
- Configuration files
- Static content
- Web.zip

This guarantees that the exact build tested during CI is deployed to the server.

---

# 25. Verify Artifact

```yaml
- script:
```

The deployment first verifies that the artifact has been downloaded successfully.

Example:

```
Deployment Stage Started

Artifact Downloaded Successfully
```

This provides confirmation before copying files to the server.

---

# 26. Copy Files to AWS EC2

The following Azure DevOps task is used:

```yaml
CopyFilesOverSSH@0
```

## Purpose

Transfers the published application from the Azure DevOps agent to the AWS EC2 instance using SSH.

Source

```
$(Pipeline.Workspace)/drop
```

Destination

```
/home/ec2-user/deploy
```

Files are copied securely over an encrypted SSH connection.

Advantages:

- Secure transfer
- Automatic overwrite
- No manual SCP commands
- Integrated with Azure DevOps

---

# 27. SSH Deployment

After copying the files, Azure DevOps opens an SSH session on the EC2 instance.

The remaining deployment steps execute directly on the Linux server.

---

# 28. set -e

The deployment script begins with:

```bash
set -e
```

## Purpose

Immediately stops the deployment if any command returns a non-zero exit code.

Without this command:

- Deployment may continue even after a failure.
- Application could become partially deployed.
- Errors might go unnoticed.

Using `set -e` ensures deployment integrity.

---

# 29. Installing unzip

```bash
sudo dnf install unzip -y
```

## Purpose

The published application is generated as a compressed ZIP file.

The Linux server requires the unzip utility to extract the deployment package.

The command is safe to execute multiple times because DNF installs the package only if it is not already present.

---

# 30. Creating Deployment Directory

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /opt/cleanarchitecture
```

## Purpose

Creates the application deployment directory.

The `-p` option ensures:

- Directory is created if it does not exist.
- No error occurs if it already exists.

Application files are deployed here.

---

# 31. Stopping Existing Application

```bash
sudo systemctl stop cleanarchitecture
```

## Purpose

Stops the currently running application before replacing files.

This prevents:

- File locking
- Partial deployments
- DLL replacement errors

The command is followed by:

```bash
|| true
```

This allows deployment to continue even if the service was not already running.

---

# 32. Creating Backup

The deployment creates a backup before replacing application files.

Example:

```
/opt/backup/cleanarchitecture_20260715_203015
```

## Why Backups?

Backups provide a rollback mechanism.

If the latest deployment fails, the previous version can be restored quickly without rebuilding the application.

This is a common practice in production deployments.

---

# 33. Cleaning Previous Deployment

```bash
sudo rm -rf /opt/cleanarchitecture/*
```

## Purpose

Removes files from the previous deployment.

This prevents:

- Old DLLs
- Obsolete JavaScript files
- Stale configuration files
- Version conflicts

Deploying over existing files without cleanup can cause unexpected runtime issues.

---

# 34. Extracting the Application

```bash
sudo unzip -o /home/ec2-user/deploy/Web.zip -d /opt/cleanarchitecture
```

## Purpose

Extracts the published application into the deployment directory.

The `-o` option overwrites existing files automatically.

The deployment package contains:

- ASP.NET Core application
- Angular frontend
- Runtime files
- Static assets

---

# 35. Setting File Ownership

```bash
sudo chown -R ec2-user:ec2-user /opt/cleanarchitecture
```

## Purpose

Ensures that the deployed files are owned by the application user.

Correct ownership prevents permission-related runtime failures.

---

# 36. Starting the Application

```bash
sudo systemctl start cleanarchitecture
```

## Purpose

Starts the application using the Linux systemd service.

Using systemd provides:

- Automatic restart on failure
- Centralized logging
- Service monitoring
- Automatic startup after server reboot

This approach is preferred over manually running:

```
dotnet Web.dll
```

---

# 37. Verifying Service Status

```bash
sudo systemctl status cleanarchitecture
```

## Purpose

Confirms that the application service started successfully.

Typical information displayed includes:

- Service state
- Process ID
- Memory usage
- CPU usage
- Recent log entries

This provides immediate deployment feedback.

---

# 38. Waiting Before Validation

```bash
sleep 10
```

## Purpose

Provides the application with sufficient time to start before performing the health check.

Without a delay, the health check may execute before the application has finished initializing.

---

# 39. Health Check

The deployment validates the application using:

```bash
curl -sSf http://localhost:5000 > /dev/null
```

## Purpose

Confirms that the application is responding successfully.

The deployment is considered successful only if the application returns an HTTP success response.

If the health check fails:

- Pipeline fails
- Deployment is reported as unsuccessful
- The issue can be investigated before users access the application

Health checks are a critical component of production deployment pipelines.

---

# 40. Continuous Deployment Summary

At the completion of the CD stage, Azure DevOps has successfully:

- Downloaded the deployment artifact
- Copied files securely to AWS EC2
- Connected to the Linux server using SSH
- Stopped the running application
- Created a deployment backup
- Removed the previous deployment
- Extracted the latest application
- Updated file ownership
- Started the application service
- Verified service health

The deployment is now complete, and the latest version of the application is available to users.

